{{italic title}}
'''''Amorosa visione''''' (1342, revised c. 1365) is a narrative poem by [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Boccaccio]], full of echoes of the ''[[Divine Comedy]]'' and consisting of 50 canti in ''[[terza rima]]''. It tells of a dream in which the poet sees, in sequence, the triumphs of Wisdom, Earthly Glory, Wealth, Love, all-destroying Fortune (and her servant Death), and thereby becomes worthy of the now heavenly love of Fiammetta. The triumphs include mythological, classical and contemporary medieval figures. Their moral, cultural and historical architecture was without precedent, and led [[Petrarch]] to create his own ''[[Trionfi (poem)|Trionfi]]'' on the same model. Among contemporaries [[Giotto]] and [[Dante Alighieri|Dante]] stand out, the latter being celebrated above any other artist, ancient or modern.

== External links ==
* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/21299/Lamorosa-visione ''L'Amorosa visione'']

