{{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Battle of Mamma |partof=the [[Muslim Conquests]] |date=690 |place=Valley of Mamma, east of [[Timgad]] in the [[Aurès Mountains]], [[Algeria]] |result=Decisive Muslim victory |combatant1= [[Umayyad|Umayyad Caliphate]] |combatant2=[[Kingdom of Altava]] |commander1=[[Zuhair bin Qais Al-Balawi]] |commander2=[[Kusaila|Caecilius]] {{KIA}} |strength1= |strength2= |casualties1= |casualties2= |campaignbox={{Campaignbox Arab–Byzantine Wars}} {{Campaignbox Berber Wars}} }}
The '''Battle of Mamma''' took place in 690 between the Arab Muslim forces of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] and the [[Berbers]] led by [[Kusaila|Caecilius]] of [[Kingdom of Altava]].
==Background== The [[Arabs|Arab]] general [[Uqba ibn Nafi]] had led his men in an expedition across north Africa, eventually reaching the Atlantic Ocean and marching as far south as the [[Draa River|Draa]] and [[Sous River|Sous]] rivers. On his return to the east, he was ambushed by the Berber-Byzantine coalition led by Caecilius at the [[Battle of Vescera]] in which he was defeated and killed in 682.<ref name=Conant>{{cite book | last = Conant | first = Jonathan | title = Staying Roman : conquest and identity in Africa and the Mediterranean, 439-700 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 0521196973 | pages = 280–281}}</ref> Caecilius at that time held undisputed mastery over North Africa and marched to [[Kairouan]] in triumph.<ref name="Conant"/>
When [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] became the [[caliph]], he was effective in increasing the size of his empire. Therefore, he ordered [[Zuhair bin Qais Al-Balawi]] who was stationed in [[Barca (ancient city)|Barca]] to lead an army to retake [[Ifriqiya]] and its capital Kairouan.
In order to mount a stronger resistance, Caecilius took a position in the [[Aurès Mountains]] in which he can manage to retreat in case of defeat, while the Muslim leader Zuhair took a decision to camp outside Kairouan near the water resources.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = El Hareir| first1 = Idris| last2 =M'Baye | first2 = Ravane| title = The Spread of Islam Throughout the World, Series: Different aspects of Islamic culture, 3| publisher = UNESCO Publishing | location = Paris, France | year = 2011 | isbn = 978-92-3-104153-2 | pages = 309}}</ref>
After a heavy battle in the valley of Mamma, the Arab invaders eventually managed to defeat the defending troops and to kill their legendary king Caecilius.
==Aftermath== The Arab leader Zuhair and his troops went back to [[Barca (ancient city)|Barca]] to fight against the invading [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]]. The incoming ships of Byzantines came with large number of soldiers in which they defeated the Arabs and killed Zuhair.
[[Dihya]] succeeded Caecilius as the war leader of the Berber tribes and opposed the encroaching Arab Islamic armies of the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad Dynasty]]. Another Arab general [[Hasan ibn al-Nu'man]] marched from Egypt and captured the major Byzantine city of [[Carthage]] and other cities after the [[Battle of Carthage (698)|Battle of Carthage]]. Searching for another enemy to defeat, he was told that the most powerful monarch in North Africa was Dihyā, and accordingly marched into [[Numidia]]. The armies met near [[Meskiana]] in the present-day province of [[Oum el-Bouaghi]], [[Algeria]]. She defeated Hasan so soundly that he fled Ifriqiya and holed up in [[Cyrenaica]] for four or five years.
