[[Image:Serie r klt 6429.png|right|thumb|R-KLT Euro 600×400mm stackable container]] A '''Euro container''' or '''KLT''' box (from {{lang-de|'''Kleinladungsträger'''}}, “small load carrier”) is an industrial stacking container conforming to the '''VDA 4500''' standard. The standard was originally defined by the [[German Association of the Automotive Industry]] (VDA) for the automotive industry but subsequently adopted across many other areas of manufacturing and the shipping industry. The most common sizes are 600mm×400mm and 400mm×300mm and meaning that these stack easily on to a [[Euro-pallet]] measuring 1200mm×800mm.
== Dimensions == {{Bar chart | float = right | title = Container heights (without feet)<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.verpackung24.com/out/azure/pdf/Kleinladungstraeger_VDA_4500.pdf|title=Kleinladungsträger (KLT)-System|number=4500|series=VDA|date=23 December 2005|accessdate=30 July 2018|language=de|quote=Höhenraster … Einheitliche Eintauchtiefe 15 mm … 2 Höhenraster … 147,5 mm … 280 mm}}</ref> | bar_width = 25 | width_units = em | label_type = Type | data_type = Stacking height increment (mm) | label2 = Normal | label3 = High | data2 = 132.5 | data3 = 265 | comment2 = 147.5 mm overall | comment3 = 280 mm overall | data_max = 300 }} Eurocontainers are based around two standard heights of {{convert|147.5|mm|in|sigfig=2}} and {{convert|280|mm|in|sigfig=2}}, including a {{convert|15|mm|inch|sigfig=1}} overlap in the vertical direction—the height of the feet, or base, stacked into the lip of the box below:
