The '''International Rhine Regulation Railway''' ({{lang-de|Internationale Rheinregulierungsbahn}}) was an [[industrial railway]] situated on both banks of the [[Alpine Rhine]] river to the south of its outfall into [[Lake Constance]]. Large parts of the line have been preserved. As this stretch of the Rhine forms the international boundary between [[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]], the railway is located in both countries.<ref name=strecke>{{cite web 
  | url = http://www.rheinschauen.at/strecke 
  | title = Strecke | language = German |trans-title=Route | publisher = Rhein-Schauen 
  | accessdate = 2014-05-28
}}</ref>

As its name suggests, the railway's original purpose was to assist in the engineering works needed to regulate the Rhine in this area - the so-called [[Rhine Regulation]]. It is constructed to [[750 mm gauge railways|750 mm gauge]] ({{track gauge|750mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge) and is partially electrified at 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] using overhead lines.<ref name=alpb>{{cite web 
  | url = http://www.alpenbahnen.net/html/rheinregulierung.html | title = Die Internationale Rheinregulierungs bahn | language = German 
  | website = alpenbahnen.net 
  | accessdate = 2014-05-28
}}</ref>

