{{Infobox organization |formation ={{start date and age|df=yes|2008}} |status =Public-private partnership |headquarters=12, rue Erasme L-1468 Luxembourg-Kirchberg |country=[[Luxembourg]] |key_people =Nicolas Mackel, CEO |affiliations= |budget = |remarks = |name = |image_border= |size = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation=LLF |num_staff = |num_volunteers= |website ={{URL|luxembourgforfinance.com}} }}
'''Luxembourg for Finance''' (LFF) is the Agency for the Development of the [[Luxembourg]] Financial Centre.
==Introduction== The agency is a public-private partnership between the Luxembourg government<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gouvernement.lu/|title=gouvernement.lu // L’actualité du gouvernement du Luxembourg - Accueil|website=www.gouvernement.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref> and the Luxembourg Financial Industry Federation<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourgforfinance.com/en/about-us/luxembourg-finance/profil-luxembourg|title=PROFIL Luxembourg|work=Luxembourg for finance|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref> which brings together the various trade bodies of the Luxembourg financial sector, such as the Luxembourg Banker’s Association, the [[Association of the Luxembourg Fund Industry#cite note-ALFI appoints Denise Voss as Chairman-2|Luxembourg Investment Fund Industry]] or the Association of Insurance and Reinsurance Companies in Luxembourg.
==Purpose== Founded in 2008, its objective is to help develop and diversify Luxembourg’s [[financial services]] industry, position the financial centre abroad and identify new business opportunities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/fr/investir/secteurs-cles/finance/acteurs-publics/index.html|title=Acteurs publics|access-date=2017-03-14|language=fr}}</ref> LFF connects international investors to the range of financial services provided in Luxembourg, such as [[investment fund]]s, [[wealth management]], capital market operations or advisory services.
==Rankings== The Luxembourg Financial Centre is ranked as the leading financial centre in the Eurozone and 2nd in the European Union after London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wort.lu/en/business/global-financial-centres-index-luxembourg-ranks-3rd-most-competitive-european-financial-centre-57062aa91bea9dff8fa75bef#|title=Global Financial Centres Index: Luxembourg ranks 3rd most competitive European financial centre|date=2016-04-07|work=Wort.lu|access-date=2017-03-14|language=en}}</ref>
==Management== Since 2013, Nicolas Mackel has been Chief Executive Officer of Luxembourg for Finance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://paperjam.lu/news/nicolas-mackel-reconduit-a-la-tete-de-lff-0|title=Nicolas Mackel reconduit à la tête de LFF|date=2017-03-03|work=Paperjam News|access-date=2017-03-14}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Luxembourg for Finance (LLF)}} [[Category:Finance in Luxembourg]]
{{Luxembourg-stub}}

{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}


The '''livre''' was the currency of [[Luxembourg]] until 1795. It was subdivided into 20 ''[[solidus (coin)|sols]]'', each of 4 ''liards''. In the late 18th century, coins were issued in denominations of ½ and 2 liards, 1, 3, 6, 12 and 72 sols, with the lower three denominations in copper, the highest minted in silver and the others in [[Billon (alloy)|billon]]. The last issues of 1795 were 1 sol coins minted during the [[Siege of Luxembourg (1794–1795)|siege of Luxembourg]].

