[[Category:Country classifications]]

Symbols of [[Latvia]] are items or symbols that have symbolic meaning to, or represent, [[Latvia]]. These symbols are seen in official capacities, such as [[flag]]s, [[coats of arms]], [[postage stamp]]s, and [[currency]], and in [[Uniform Resource Locator|URL]]s. They appear less formally as recurring themes in [[Latvian literature|literature]], art and [[folk art]], [[heraldry]], monuments, clothing, personal decoration, and as the names of parks, bridges, streets, and clubs. The less formal manifestations may be classified as [[national emblem]]s.
During the [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupation]] of Latvia by the [[Soviet Union]] and briefly by [[Nazi Germany]] during [[World War II]], the anthem, coat of arms and flag were prohibited from display and the [[Sovietization of the Baltic states|Soviet versions]] of the [[Flag of the Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|flag]], [[Emblem of the Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|coat of arms]] and the [[Anthem of the Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|anthem]] were used during its rule as a [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet republic]]. All national symbols of Latvia were reinstated in 1990 before Latvia restored its independence a year later which are considered the [[State continuity of the Baltic states|continuation]] of the Latvian state before its occupation in 1940. The public display of the [[Nazi]] [[swastika]] and the Soviet [[hammer and sickle]] along with other symbols associated with them are now banned in Latvia in 2014.
